sequenceDiagram
    participant User as User's Browser
    participant SPA as Single-Page App<br/>(JavaScript Client)
    participant AS as Authorization Server

    Note over User,AS: Implicit Flow (RFC 6749 Section 4.2)<br/>DEPRECATED - Do NOT use in new applications

    rect rgb(255, 235, 238)
        Note over SPA,AS: The Problem: Token exposed in URL fragment
        SPA->>User: Redirect to Authorization Server
        Note right of SPA: GET /authorize?<br/>response_type=token<br/>&client_id=spa_abc<br/>&redirect_uri=https://app.example.com/callback<br/>&scope=openid profile<br/>&state=abc123

        User->>AS: Browser follows redirect
        AS->>User: Login + consent screen
        User->>AS: Approve

        AS->>User: 302 Redirect with token IN FRAGMENT
        Note right of AS: 302 Location:<br/>https://app.example.com/callback<br/>#access_token=eyJhbGciOiJS...<br/>&token_type=Bearer<br/>&expires_in=3600<br/>&state=abc123
    end

    User->>SPA: Browser loads callback page<br/>Fragment is NOT sent to server<br/>JavaScript extracts token from URL

    rect rgb(255, 235, 238)
        Note over User,AS: SECURITY VULNERABILITIES
        Note over User: 1. Token in browser history<br/>URL fragment is visible in history
        Note over User: 2. Token in Referer header<br/>Leaked to third-party scripts on the page
        Note over User: 3. No client authentication<br/>Any app can use the same client_id
        Note over User: 4. No PKCE protection<br/>Code interception attacks possible
        Note over User: 5. Token replay<br/>No binding between token and client
        Note over User: 6. No refresh token<br/>User must re-authorize when token expires
    end

    Note over User,AS: REPLACEMENT: Use Authorization Code + PKCE instead<br/>OAuth 2.1 formally removes the Implicit Grant
